Ah, now I understand exactly what you‚Äôre asking ‚Äî you‚Äôre seeing dates appear in your React frontend, but you never actually inserted any date in MongoDB, because your collection is basically empty except for placeholder/example items. Let‚Äôs clarify how the **dates are being set and sent** to the frontend.

---

### 1Ô∏è‚É£ WordPress posts

For WordPress posts, the date comes from WordPress itself:

```ts
const posts = postsResponse.data.map(post => ({
  ...post,
  type: "wp",
  id: `wp-${post.id}`,
}));
```

* `post.date` is provided by WordPress.
* The frontend displays it here:

```ts
{new Date(item.date).toLocaleDateString("en-US", { ... })}
```

So WordPress is the source of the date for the `wp` items.

---

### 2Ô∏è‚É£ Static Dortmund news (`/api/news`)

In your backend, you had this:

```js
const dortmundNews = [
  {
    id: "news-1",
    title: "Dortmund City Development News",
    link: "...",
    description: "...",
    date: new Date().toISOString(),
    source: "Stadt Dortmund",
    type: "news"
  },
  ...
];
```

Notice:

```js
date: new Date().toISOString()
```

* These dates are **generated at runtime** when your server responds.
* That means every time you restart your backend or fetch `/api/news`, it creates new dates for these items, even though there‚Äôs no real date in a database.
* They are ‚Äúfake‚Äù dates for demo purposes.

---

### 3Ô∏è‚É£ MongoDB news items

When you fetch MongoDB items in `/api/content`:

```js
const mongoFormatted = mongoNews.map((item) => ({
  ...item,
  id: `mongo-${item._id}`,
  title: { rendered: item.title },
  excerpt: { rendered: item.description || item.content?.slice(0, 150) || "" },
  content: { rendered: item.content || item.description || "" },
  date: item.date || new Date().toISOString(),
  source: item.source || "MongoDB Feed",
  type: "news",
}));
```

* `date: item.date || new Date().toISOString()`

Here‚Äôs the key:

1. If your MongoDB document **has a `date` field**, it will use that.
2. If your MongoDB document **does not have a date**, it will automatically generate `new Date().toISOString()` ‚Äî i.e., the current timestamp.

This is why your frontend sees dates even though your cluster has no real ‚Äúnews‚Äù with dates.

---

### 4Ô∏è‚É£ Sending dates to the client

* The backend sends the combined array via `/api/content`.
* Each item has a `date` field.
* Your React component uses:

```ts
{new Date(item.date).toLocaleDateString("en-US", { ... })}
```

So the **client page is just displaying whatever `date` the backend sends**, regardless of its origin.

---

### ‚úÖ Summary

| Source          | Where the date comes from                           |
| --------------- | --------------------------------------------------- |
| WordPress posts | WordPress API (`post.date`)                         |
| Static news     | Generated dynamically with `new Date()`             |
| MongoDB news    | `item.date` in MongoDB if exists, else `new Date()` |

---

### üîπ Next Steps

If you want **real dates for MongoDB news**:

1. Add a `date` field when you insert items in MongoDB.
   Example:

```js
await News.create({
  title: "Some news",
  description: "Description",
  content: "Content",
  link: "...",
  source: "News Source",
  date: new Date("2025-11-01T10:00:00Z")
});
```

2. Or, if you‚Äôre scraping from a real source, extract the publication date and store it in the MongoDB document.

